# User Preferences

The Pref architecture is in place but no preferences are currently implemented. Use this pattern when adding new ones.

Preferences are persisted to Firestore via `usePrefsStore()` from `~/composables/usePrefsStore.ts`, backed by `FirestorePrefsStore` which calls `/api/firestore/*` endpoints. Auth is required.

## Two-Tier Namespacing

Preferences are scoped by the app ID set in `NUXT_PUBLIC_APP_ID`:

- **App-specific**: `/users/{userId}/apps/{appId}/settings/general` -- feature settings, watchlists
- **Global (cross-app)**: `/users/{userId}/global/settings/general` -- language, accessibility, timezone

## The Pref Class

`Pref<T>` is a reactive wrapper that auto-syncs to Firestore. It's defined in `usePrefsStore.ts`.

```typescript
const myPref = new Pref<string>(docPath, 'fieldName', 'defaultValue');
await myPref.initialize();

myPref.r.value; // reactive ref (use in templates)
myPref.v;       // getter shorthand
myPref.set('new value'); // persists to Firestore
```

Values are JSON-serialized in Firestore. The `Pref` sets up a watcher after `initialize()` so any change to `.r` auto-persists.

## usePrefsStore()

```typescript
const { readDoc, listCollections, listDocuments, deleteCollection } = usePrefsStore();
```

`initializePrefsStore()` must run first (handled by app startup).

## Module-Level Preferences

Feature modules should namespace under the app's prefix:

```typescript
function useMyModulePrefs() {
    const { appId } = useRuntimeConfig().public;
    const { userId } = useUserState();
    const path = `/users/${userId.value}/apps/${appId}/modules/my-module`;

    const myPref = new Pref<boolean>(path, 'enabled', true);
    return { myPref };
}
```

## Scope Guidance

| App-specific | Global |
|---|---|
| Layout prefs, favorites | Language |
| Watchlists, feature settings | Accessibility |
| Module-specific settings | Timezone, notifications |
